## TabBar Component

The `TabBar` component provides a user interface for managing and switching between different tabs. It allows users to navigate between tabs, close existing ones (if more than one tab is present), and add new tabs.

### Purpose

This component is designed to be a reusable UI element for applications that require a tabbed interface, such as code editors or multi-document interfaces.

### Key Exports

*   **`TabBar`**: The main React component for rendering the tab bar.

### Props

*   **`tabs`** (`Tab[]`): An array of `Tab` objects, where each `Tab` object must have at least an `id` (string) and a `label` (string). The `id` is used for identification and state management, while the `label` is displayed as the tab's text.
*   **`activeTabId`** (`string`): The ID of the currently active tab. This prop is used to visually highlight the active tab.
*   **`onSwitch`** (`(id: string) => void`): A callback function that is invoked when a tab is clicked to switch to it. It receives the `id` of the clicked tab.
*   **`onClose`** (`(id: string) => void`): A callback function that is triggered when a tab's close button is clicked or when a tab is closed using the middle mouse button. It receives the `id` of the tab to be closed.
*   **`onAdd`** (`() => void`): A callback function that is invoked when the "New tab" button is clicked. This is typically used to open a new tab in the application.

### Usage Example

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { TabBar } from './TabBar'; // Assuming TabBar.tsx is in the same directory
import type { Tab } from './types'; // Assuming types.ts defines the Tab interface

const App: React.FC = () => {
  const [tabs, setTabs] = useState<Tab[]>([
    { id: 'tab1', label: 'Tab 1' },
    { id: 'tab2', label: 'Tab 2' },
  ]);
  const [activeTabId, setActiveTabId] = useState<string>('tab1');

  const handleSwitchTab = (id: string) => {
    setActiveTabId(id);
  };

  const handleCloseTab = (id: string) => {
    setTabs(tabs.filter(tab => tab.id !== id));
    if (activeTabId === id && tabs.length > 1) {
      // If the closed tab was active, switch to the next available tab
      setActiveTabId(tabs.find(tab => tab.id !== id)?.id || '');
    } else if (tabs.length === 1) {
      // If it was the last tab, reset activeTabId or handle appropriately
      setActiveTabId('');
    }
  };

  const handleAddTab = () => {
    const newTabId = `tab${tabs.length + 1}`;
    setTabs([...tabs, { id: newTabId, label: `Tab ${tabs.length + 1}` }]);
    setActiveTabId(newTabId);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <TabBar
        tabs={tabs}
        activeTabId={activeTabId}
        onSwitch={handleSwitchTab}
        onClose={handleCloseTab}
        onAdd={handleAddTab}
      />
      {/* Render content for the active tab here */}
      <div style={{ marginTop: '20px' }}>
        {activeTabId === 'tab1' && <div>Content for Tab 1</div>}
        {activeTabId === 'tab2' && <div>Content for Tab 2</div>}
        {/* ... other tab content */}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

**Note:** The `Tab` interface is expected to be defined in a separate `types` file (e.g., `types.ts` or `types.d.ts`). It should minimally include `id: string` and `label: string`.
